        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe in CO(1-0) a region in Cen A of 2'x3' centered on approximately 13:26:21 -42:50:17 (J2000) and located between the outer filament (covering the bright part of the filament) and the HI shell, see Fig. 2 of the scientific justification. The region will be covered by 39 pointing.

Requested Sensitivity

Our sensitivity estimate is based on SEST observations of CO 1-0 emitting gas on top of the HI shells (Charmandaris et al. 2000). They measured a peak CO 1-0 line intensity of 810 mJy within a 44 arcsec (FWHM) beam. From higher resolution optical observations of the Cen A filaments (Oonk et al. in prep) and similar filaments in other galaxies such as Perseus A (Fabian at
al. 2008) we know that these filaments are in fact very narrow pc-scale structures and that their filling factor is at most 0.1 as measured relative to the large SEST beam.

Very likely the CO 1-0, associated with coldest cores of these filaments, has an even lower filling factor. Here we will assume a conservative upper estimate of 0.1 for the filling factor of t he CO 1-0 emitting gas in the Cen A filaments.

Combining the filling factor and the SEST measurement we expect a peak CO 1-0 flux of 21 mJy per 2''x2'' (i.e. 40x40 pc2) resolution element for the filaments in Cen A. Our aim is to detect this CO 1-0 emitting gas across the indicated 2'x3' area down to a uniform sensitivity of 3 mJy per 2'' (FWHM) beam and 10 km/s velocity resolution. This sensitivity and resolution corresponds to a 1 sigma detection threshold of a 4500 Msun molecular mass per 1600 pc2, or about 3 Msun per pc2 (Bolatto, Wolfire &amp; Leroy 2013).

For comparison, typical Milky Way GMC's have molecular masses corresponding to about 100 Msun/pc2 and sizes of a few tens to a few hundred pc. Our expected conservative upper limit to the CO 1-0 line signal of 21 mJy per 2'' beam then means that with ALMA we will detect these clouds with peak SNR of 7 and spatially resolve them.

The expected narrow structure of filaments means that the 22 arcsec (i.e. 0.5 kpc) maximum resolvable scale requested in this proposal is more than sufficient to ensure that these are not resolved out by ALMA.

To search for potentially low-level, diffuse gas between the filaments we will subtract the bright small structures (i.e. cold cores) from the data and restore it at various spatial resolutions. Furthermore the observational setup for the CO 1-0 line, with 0.6 km/s channels, will also allow us to search and characterize the brightest, potentially very dynamically cold (dv &lt; 10 km /s) clumps in the filaments.

The ALMA OT2 time estimator shows that we can obtain the requested uniform sensitivity of 3 mJy per 2'' (FWHM) beam and 10 km/s velocity resolution over a 2'x3' area in 3.6 hours total (i .e. incl. calibration).

The other basebands will be used to search for the 3 mm cold dust continuum emission from the filaments down to a level of about 0.075 mJy per 2'' beam. This corresponds to a detection threshold of about 2150 Msun of total emitting mass per 1600 pc2, or about 1.3 Msun per pc2 (Sollins, Zhang &amp; Ho 2003). 
This will allow us to probe the dust-to-gas distribution and ratio in the filaments of Cen A. We propose to use one of the continuum basebands in FDM low resolution mode to additionally cover the H2CO line at 101GHz as a bonus tracer of high density gas.


Correlator Setup

The CO (1-0) line is redshifted to 115.06 GHz, where we will center the main baseband with a bandwidth of 1221 km/s and with 0.6 km/s resolution. Two basebands (2 and 4) are set to TDM. Baseband 3 is set to the low-resolution FDM and covers the H2CO line, but can be used for continuum as well.</prj:justificationText>
