    <prp:abstract>We propose to investigate the presence and properties of molecular gas (CO(1-0)) in the two complex regions of Centaurus A, the inner and outer filaments, with particular emphasis on the interface between the filaments of ionized gas and the radio plasma.
In these regions, signatures of interaction between the radio jet/lobe and the ISM have been observed and star-formation is occurring  as result of such interaction.
Thus, with the proposed ALMA observations we will explore, in the nearest AGN, processes connected to negative and positive feedback that we are seen at work in more distant objects. The properties of the molecular gas, its distribution and kinematics will be used as tracer of its evolution under the influence of the radio plasma and how this is linked to the formation of stars.  
The selected regions encompass all the relevant structures â€“ ionized filaments, part of the HI shell including the region with disturbed kinematics, star forming regions, radio jet/lobes - key for obtaining a full view of the ongoing processes and have a plethora of multi-wavelengths data available</prp:abstract>
